\pard\f0\fs28\qc {\b 2.               Phacelia}              Juss.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc By †T.G. Tutin.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Annual herbs. Leaves alternate. Flowers in scorpioid inflorescences, shortly pedicellate. Calyx without appendages between the lobes. Corolla rotate to campanulate. Filaments with append ages at their base.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. P. tanacetifolia} Bentham, {\i Trans. Linn. Soc. London}{\b  17}: 280 (1835). Stems 20-80 cm, glandular-pubescent and hispid, usually erect and simple or sparingly branched. Leaves 2-10 cm, shortly petiolate, ovate to ovate-oblong in outline, 1- to 2-pinnatisect. Calyx-lobes (5-)6-8, usually linear. Corolla 6-9 mm, blue, persistent. Stamens long-exserted. Styles connate for c. 1 mm. Capsule 3-4 mm, ovoid, pubescent at apex.{\i  Cultivated for bees and frequently naturalized.} [Au Be Bu Cz Da Ga He Ho Hu Ju Lu No Po Rm Rs (B, C, W, E) Su.] ({\i W. North America}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Several other species of this large American genus are cultivated and some have been recorded as more or less naturalized. The two commonest of these are: {\b P. ciliata} Bentham, {\i loc. cit.} (1835), with a strongly accrescent calyx, and{\b  P. minor} (Harvey) Thell.,{\i  Ber. Bayer. Bot. Ges. }{\b 14}: 79 (1914), with pedicels up to 15 mm and the styles connate to above the middle.
\par

